---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { indexes } from "../lib/siteData";

const rows = indexes();
const weights: Record<string, number> = {
  value: 0.2,
  momentum: 0.25,
  quality: 0.25,
  volatility: 0.1,
  sentiment: 0.2,
};
---

<Base title="Index methodology">
  <h1>How the Bullwright Score works</h1>
  <p>
    Each index turns point-in-time data for one ticker into a raw value, which is
    normalized cross-sectionally (winsorized at p5/p95, min-max to 0–100) across the
    watchlist for that date. The composite is a weighted blend; missing indexes
    redistribute their weight pro-rata, and if more than half the weight is missing the
    score is reported as insufficient data — never a fake neutral.
  </p>
  {rows.length === 0 && <p class="meta">run <code>bw quant score</code> + <code>bw export-blog</code> to populate this page</p>}
  {
    rows.map((idx) => (
      <article class="card">
        <h2 style="margin:0 0 0.2rem;">
          {idx.index_key}
          <span class="meta" style="font-weight:400;">
            {" "}
            v{idx.version} · {idx.direction.replaceAll("_", " ")} · default weight{" "}
            {((weights[idx.index_key] ?? 0) * 100).toFixed(0)}%
          </span>
        </h2>
        <p style="margin:0.2rem 0 0;">{idx.description}</p>
      </article>
    ))
  }
  <p class="meta">
    Look-ahead is structurally impossible: index code can only see data observed on or
    before the scoring date, and a canary test enforces it for every index, forever.
  </p>
</Base>
